T1  - Food security and agricultural production strategies under risk in Egypt
AU  - Sarris, Alexander H.
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 19
IS  - 1
SP  - 85
EP  - 111
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/09/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(85)90040-9
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387885900409
AB  - Food security is defined as the satisfaction of national food consumption needs with certainty. A methodology is developed to optimize a country's exposure to foreign agricultural price and domestic yield risks by adjusting the domestic agricultural production structure, subject to the food security objective. The method is empirically implemented for Egypt. It is shown that under low degrees of national risk aversion Egypt should specialize its agricultural production more toward cash and export crops, while under high degrees of national risk aversion the country should produce more basic staple foods. The nature of the constraints facing Egyptian agriculture is explored in the context of the above definition of food security.
